347. Top K Frequent Elements
Problem

Given an integer array nums and an integer k, return the k most frequent elements.

Example
Input: nums = [1,1,1,2,2,3], k = 2
Output: [1,2]

Approach 1: Brute Force (Repeated Maximum Frequency Scan)
Intuition
Count frequency using HashMap.
Repeat k times:
Find the element with maximum frequency.
Add it to answer.
Mark its frequency as 0.
Java Solution
class Solution {
    public int[] topKFrequent(int[] nums, int k) {

        HashMap<Integer, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();

        for (int x : nums) {
            map.put(x, map.getOrDefault(x, 0) + 1);
        }

        int[] ans = new int[k];

        for (int i = 0; i < k; i++) {

            int maxFreq = 0;
            int maxElement = 0;

            for (Map.Entry<Integer, Integer> entry : map.entrySet()) {

                if (entry.getValue() > maxFreq) {
                    maxFreq = entry.getValue();
                    maxElement = entry.getKey();
                }
            }

            ans[i] = maxElement;
            map.put(maxElement, 0);
        }

        return ans;
    }
}
Dry Run
nums = [1,1,1,2,2,3]

Frequency Map:

1 → 3
2 → 2
3 → 1

Iteration 1:

Max Frequency = 3 → Pick 1

Iteration 2:

Max Frequency = 2 → Pick 2

Answer:

[1,2]
Complexity
Time: O(n + k·m)
Space: O(m)

m = number of unique elements

Approach 2: Sorting by Frequency
Intuition
Count frequencies.
Convert map entries into a list.
Sort descending by frequency.
Pick first k elements.
Java Solution
class Solution {
    public int[] topKFrequent(int[] nums, int k) {

        Map<Integer, Integer> freq = new HashMap<>();

        for (int num : nums) {
            freq.put(num, freq.getOrDefault(num, 0) + 1);
        }

        List<Map.Entry<Integer, Integer>> list =
                new ArrayList<>(freq.entrySet());

        list.sort((a, b) -> b.getValue() - a.getValue());

        int[] ans = new int[k];

        for (int i = 0; i < k; i++) {
            ans[i] = list.get(i).getKey();
        }

        return ans;
    }
}
Complexity
Time: O(n log n)
Space: O(n)

Approach 3: Min Heap
Intuition

Maintain a Min Heap of size k.

Store elements according to frequency.
If heap size exceeds k, remove smallest frequency.
Remaining elements are top k frequent.
Java Solution
class Solution {
    public int[] topKFrequent(int[] nums, int k) {

        Map<Integer, Integer> freq = new HashMap<>();

        for (int num : nums) {
            freq.put(num, freq.getOrDefault(num, 0) + 1);
        }

        PriorityQueue<Integer> pq =
                new PriorityQueue<>((a, b) ->
                        freq.get(a) - freq.get(b));

        for (int num : freq.keySet()) {

            pq.offer(num);

            if (pq.size() > k) {
                pq.poll();
            }
        }

        int[] ans = new int[k];

        for (int i = k - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
            ans[i] = pq.poll();
        }

        return ans;
    }
}
Dry Run

Frequency Map:

1 → 3
2 → 2
3 → 1

Heap Operations:

Add 1 → [1]
Add 2 → [2,1]
Add 3 → [3,1,2]

Size > k
Remove 3

Remaining:

[1,2]
Complexity
Time: O(n log k)
Space: O(n)

Approach 4: Bucket Sort (Optimal)
Intuition

Maximum frequency of any element can be at most n.

Create buckets:

bucket[i] = elements appearing i times

Traverse buckets from highest frequency to lowest.

Java Solution
class Solution {
    public int[] topKFrequent(int[] nums, int k) {

        Map<Integer, Integer> freq = new HashMap<>();

        for (int num : nums) {
            freq.put(num, freq.getOrDefault(num, 0) + 1);
        }

        List<Integer>[] bucket =
                new ArrayList[nums.length + 1];

        for (int num : freq.keySet()) {

            int f = freq.get(num);

            if (bucket[f] == null) {
                bucket[f] = new ArrayList<>();
            }

            bucket[f].add(num);
        }

        int[] ans = new int[k];
        int idx = 0;

        for (int i = bucket.length - 1;
             i >= 0 && idx < k;
             i--) {

            if (bucket[i] != null) {

                for (int num : bucket[i]) {

                    ans[idx++] = num;

                    if (idx == k) {
                        break;
                    }
                }
            }
        }

        return ans;
    }
}
Dry Run

Input:

nums = [1,1,1,2,2,3]
k = 2

Frequency Map:

1 → 3
2 → 2
3 → 1

Buckets:

bucket[1] = [3]
bucket[2] = [2]
bucket[3] = [1]

Traverse from end:

bucket[3] → add 1
bucket[2] → add 2

Answer:

[1,2]
Complexity
Time: O(n)
Space: O(n)
Interview Summary
Approach	Time	Space
Repeated Max Scan	O(n + k·m)	O(m)
Sorting	O(n log n)	O(n)
Min Heap	O(n log k)	O(n)
Bucket Sort (Optimal)	O(n)	O(n)
Interview Flow
1. HashMap + Repeated Scan (Brute Force)

2. HashMap + Sorting

3. HashMap + Min Heap

4. HashMap + Bucket Sort (Optimal)
Key Takeaway
Use HashMap to count frequencies.
If asked for the best solution, use Bucket Sort (O(n)).
If k is very small compared to n, Min Heap (O(n log k)) is also an excellent choice.
